I often wonder about that. I like to read about Ottoman history, and
recently, due to some reading I've done (about the way Ataturk secularized
the country) , I've begun to follow the Turkish daily press.  The Armenian
genocide took place before Turkey became a Republic, under the &quot;ancien
regime&quot;,  and while there may be legal repercussions (such as demands for
reparations, or lawsuits for lost property)  I cannot fathom why ther Turks
don't just put this behind them. It was probably more difficult for the
Nazis to admit the Holocaust. So admit it, declare it off limits for
reparations (was before our regime)  and get on with your life.

Instead, the Turks wage a constant war against  anyone who so much as
mentions it,  prosecute any Turk who so much as mentions or writes about it,
and are fighting to rewrite history in an age where it is increasingly
difficult to do so.  Recalling their ambassador from Washington  and
threatening to stop cooperation with the US over Iraq is not the adult thing
to do.

Then again, in an age when the leaders of Iran, North Korea, and Burma (not
to mention Russia)  seem to top any possible outrage, maybe the Turks are
the normal ones.

Jay
